{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"443b992e-a4a8-492d-b956-dd79657c626d","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides were replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You hook into them by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()` directly.\n\nFor **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.OnResignActivation(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da4a706b-eaea-4dce-bec7-07f6fbf9fc78","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or override the `CreateWindow` method and hook into `Window` events.\n\nSpecifically:\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event\n\n\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated`\n\nActually, I need to clarify this — the `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't expose `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` as overridable methods like it did in Xamarin.Forms, so you'll need to use the `Window` events or configure lifecycle events through the `MauiProgram` instead. Alternatively, I can create a custom `Window` subclass and override the lifecycle methods directly—`OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()`—which gives me a cleaner way to handle app lifecycle logic in MAUI.","outputTokens":915,"requestId":"980F:204067:1657A94:18EC537:6A051F2B"},"id":"55ca70b6-12fb-43b9-bbc3-8a209139324a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:02:51.850Z","parentId":"8810bc79-178c-4344-b4af-576b05e6bf66"}
